// TEST: exec_optional_match_expr_position
// EXPECT: output "11;0"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// An Optional `match` in *expression* position with *non-`return`* arms (each
// arm yields a value, here arithmetic / a literal). This is the case the Python
// secondary defect mis-compiled:
//
//   "${match o { Some(x) => x + 1 None => 0 }}"
//
// Before the fix Python's expression-position match emitted a hardcoded
//   (lambda __v: (x + 1) if False else 0)(o)
// which (a) always selected the *last* arm (`if False`), and (b) never bound
// the `Some` payload (`x` undefined). So `Some(10)` yielded `0`, not `11`.
// Fixed by emitting a real conditional over the bound scrutinee:
//   (lambda __v: (lambda x: (x + 1))(__v._0) if isinstance(__v, _BockSome) else (0))(o)
// The other four targets already lowered this correctly.
//
// The scrutinee is interpolated (`${...}`) rather than assigned to a typed
// local. Go's expression-position Optional match lowers to a
// `func() interface{} { ... }()` IIFE whose result is `interface{}`; assigning
// that to a *typed* local (`let r: Int = match ...`) needs the match's result
// type, which the Go emitter does not infer (see the FOUND note in the PR).
// `fmt.Sprintf("%v", ...)` accepts `interface{}`, so the interpolation shape
// exercises the expression-position lowering on all five targets without
// tripping that separate, pre-existing Go limitation.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

fn pick(o: Int?) -> String {
  return "${match o { Some(x) => x + 1 None => 0 }}"
}

fn main() -> Void {
  println("${pick(Some(10))};${pick(None)}")
}
